Welcome to this special edition of Tax Confidential, bringing you the latest and most crucial updates in the world of Goods and Services Tax (GST) as of December 24, 2025. Today's highlights include a significant High Court judgment on Input Tax Credit (ITC), a Public Interest Litigation concerning GST on air purifiers, and an overview of key GST reforms and clarifications from the past year.

Key Judicial Pronouncements

Gauhati High Court on ITC Denial Due to Supplier Non-Compliance

In a landmark ruling, the Gauhati High Court addressed the denial of Input Tax Credit (ITC) to a purchaser solely because the supplier failed to comply with GSTR-1 filing and the details were not reflected in GSTR-2A/2B. The Court held that Section 16(2)(aa) of the CGST Act and AGST Act must be "read down" to prevent cascading effects and protect bona fide recipients. Authorities are now required to provide an opportunity for the purchaser to prove their bona fides with invoices and other documents before denying ITC, pending a practical administrative solution from the CBIC. The court acknowledged that the provision itself is not unconstitutional but found the condition iniquitous as it places an impossible burden on the recipient. This reading down will operate until the CBIC devises a comprehensive practical solution.

*Citation: MCLEOD Russel India Ltd. v. Union of India, [2025] 181 taxmann.com 322 (Gauhati), decided on December 9, 2025.*

Latest GST Developments & Insights

PIL in Delhi High Court Seeks Reclassification of Air Purifiers as Medical Devices

A Public Interest Litigation (PIL) has been filed in the Delhi High Court requesting the reclassification of air purifiers as "medical devices" to reduce their GST rate from 18% to 5%. The petition argues that air purifiers are a necessity, particularly in light of severe air pollution in Delhi-NCR, and should not be taxed as luxury items. The matter is scheduled for hearing today, December 24, 2025, highlighting the inconsistency in taxing them at a higher rate compared to most other medical devices which attract 5% GST.

ICAI Releases Revised Handbook on GST Interest, Late Fee, and Penalties

The Institute of Chartered Accountants of India (ICAI) has released a revised edition of its "Handbook on Interest, Late Fee and Penalties under GST" in December 2025. This updated guide incorporates the latest statutory amendments, notifications, and clarifications, offering detailed guidance on interest for delayed tax payments and wrongly availed ITC, along with comprehensive clarity on late fees and penalties.

GST Reductions Contribute to India's Economic Growth: UBS Report

A report by UBS released on December 24, 2025, indicates that GST reductions, along with targeted income tax cuts and supportive monetary policy, have significantly contributed to sustaining India's strong economic growth momentum throughout 2025. The report noted an above-trend GDP expansion of 8.2% in the September quarter.

Key GST Reforms and Trends in 2025

  • Operationalization of GST Appellate Tribunal (GSTAT): Aimed at streamlining dispute resolution and reducing the burden on High Courts.
  • GST Rate Rationalization: A major simplification implemented in September 2025, consolidating the structure into fewer slabs: 5% for essential items, 18% as the standard rate, and 40% for luxury and sin goods. This "GST 2.0" initiative sought to create a more consistent and predictable indirect tax framework.
  • Addressing Revenue Loopholes: Amendment of Section 17(5)(d) of the CGST Act retrospectively through the Finance Act, 2025, impacting Input Tax Credit on construction costs.
  • Business-Friendly Changes: Introduction of changes such as the removal of rigid requirements for post-sale discount adjustments.

Punjab's GST Collections Surge

Punjab's Finance Minister Harpal Singh Cheema reported that the state's GST collections increased by 16.03% to Rs 17,860.09 crore until November of the current fiscal year, reflecting improved taxpayer compliance and economic recovery.

CBIC Corner: Recent Circulars & Clarifications

The Central Board of Indirect Taxes and Customs (CBIC) has issued several significant circulars in 2025, providing crucial clarifications and guidelines.

  • Circular dated October 27, 2025: Provides directions under Section 168 of the CGST Act concerning the non-transition of CENVAT credit under Section 140 of the CGST Act or non-utilisation thereof in certain cases. (Full Circular Number not provided in current updates).
  • Circular dated October 1, 2025: Addresses the assigning of proper officers under Section 74A, Section 75(2), and Section 122 of the Central Goods and Services Tax Act, 2017. (Full Circular Number not provided in current updates).
  • Circular dated September 23, 2025: Announces the withdrawal of an earlier circular, No. 212/6/2024-GST. (Full Circular Number for withdrawal not provided in current updates).
  • Corrigendum to Circular No. 237/31/2024-GST dated October 15, 2024: A corrigendum was issued to correct the stated circular. (Full Circular Number for corrigendum not provided in current updates, issued implicitly in 2025).

Additional new circulars from 2025, for which specific numbers and dates were not detailed, include clarifications on GST rates and classification of goods based on recommendations from the GST Council's 53rd and 55th meetings, applicability of GST on certain services, guidelines for CSD refund applications, and issues pertaining to taxability and valuation of corporate guarantees between related persons.
